      "name": "PIV velocity field comparison — FDA generic pump",
      "description": "Computational velocity fields compared against particle image velocimetry (PIV) measurements from the FDA benchmark dataset. Mean relative error 18.3% at design point; errors increase to 27.1% at off-design VAD operating conditions. Achieved validation level insufficient for MRL 5 absolute hemolysis prediction.",
      "validationMetric": "Mean relative error",
      "achievedAccuracy": "18.3% at design point; 27.1% off-design"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/hemolysis-index-absolute-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Absolute hemolysis index validation against in-vitro measurements",
      "description": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against five in-vitro test conditions spanning the VAD operating envelope. Model over-predicts NIH by a factor of 1.4–2.1 depending on operating point. Monte Carlo UQ campaign (5000 runs, Latin hypercube sampling) confirmed that model-form uncertainty in the power-law hemolysis constitutive equation dominates total variance (Sobol first-order index S1=0.61), followed by blood viscosity uncertainty (S1=0.19). Despite the UQ campaign, prediction intervals remain too wide to support absolute threshold decisions. Sensitivity decomposition discussed in the UQ campaign report referenced in wasDerivedFrom.",
      "validationMetric": "Normalized Index of Hemolysis (NIH)",
      "achievedAccuracy": "Factor 1.4–2.1 over-prediction across 5 operating points"
    },
    {
